description.plain:
“THAT GIRL” is the lead single from Bree Runway’s upcoming debut studio album. The song was released on September 29, after being announced 2 days prior. The powerful song is filled with hyperpop elements, which is no surprise as it is produced by EASYFUN, who is a big name in the genre.

Bree described how she feels about the song to PAPER magazine:

This song automatically makes me feel like the main character in the middle of a sweaty club, and I’m just oozing sex, glamour and confidence whilst everybody watches. It’s my everyday reminder of how fabulous I am, and it’s your new everyday reminder too – you’re automatically a 10 if you: turn this on, fuck with it, press play and feel liberated, pumped up, and free.

annotations: My body look good in that new Gaultier

Gaultier is a French luxury fashion house, founded by fashion designer Jean Paul Gaultier. In the 1980’s, the house gained notoriety for their cone-breasted designs, which became infamous when Madonna wore them during her Blond Ambition World Tour.

https://www.instagram.com/p/B7dudkhB1pY/
I can pronounce everything I wear

Bree is known to wear a lot of expensive clothes, made from luxury fashion houses like Gaultier, Chanel, Balenciaga, Louis Vuitton, Givenchy, and more. As these houses were mostly founded in Europe, the names can be quite hard to pronounce for non-native speakers. Besides Bree being able to afford them, she can also correctly pronounce the fashion house they’re from, which is a double flex. It makes her different from the majority, and it also suggests that she might have close ties with the houses.

Shortly after “THAT GIRL” got released, Bree made a TikTok to give everyone a crash course in correctly pronouncing fashion houses.
These bitches cap like New Era
Bree compares how “these bitches” lie, or in African American Vernacular English, “cap”, to the brand New Era, known for their sports-branded fitted caps.
Get your ass on the runway, it’s a whole new world, uh

This might be a nod to “Whole New World/Pretend World”, a track by the late SOPHIE, a bubblegum bass and hyperpop innovator who worked and produced along with EASYFUN, who is credited as the producer on this song.

“THAT GIRL” is heavily infused with hyperpop production, possibly making a homage to SOPHIE, who is mainly responsible for the expansion and popularization of the genre.

description.plain:
“HOT HOT” was supposed to be the first single from Bree Runway’s upcoming debut album. The song was released with a music video on March 31, 2021.

Shortly after the song got released, trouble ensued as the sample – Busta Rhymes' “Touch It” – didn’t get cleared. Bree had to update the song with a slightly different beat on streaming platforms and even the official music video, leaving behind the original sample.

https://twitter.com/breerunway/status/1390754404555534343

Because of this situation, she later clarified to a fan on Twitter that the song will not be a part of her debut album.

https://twitter.com/breerunway/status/1423080215098519553?s=20

annotations: Ride that boy face like a Yamaha

Yamaha Motor are a Japanese manufacturer of motorcycles, and are the manufacturer of the motorcycle pictured in the promotional imagery for this single. She is pictured in several different positions on the vehicle in this promotional material, it can be assumed this’d be similar to when she’s in the situation she describes here.
You can never ever do it like a Brenda

When Bree says the line it sounds like “brander”.

Her real name is Brenda Wireko Mensah, saying “you could never ever do it like me”.

annotatable.title: GUCCI

annotations: I like bitches that ain’t wit the beefin’ long as they vegan (Ah)

Maliibu Miitch loves supporting fellow female rappers like Bree Runway, Qveen Herby, Brooke Candy & Nicki Minaj as long as they don’t fight her.
Also the vegan line is wordplay on the double meaning of beef.
Spent a couple racks, I did

Bree isn’t shy about displaying her designer escapades. She frequently is seen wearing many designer brands on her social media platforms like Gucci (the song’s namesake), Dior, Chanel, and many, many more. She is usually seen wearing these alongside her good friend, model Leomie Anderson.
In my own lane these bitches got traffic

Bree knows that she is an upper-echelon piece and is focused on her own goals and aspirations.

Every now and then, she can look on the other side of the road and see that “bitches got traffic” simply because they’re all following the same formula, whatever that may be.

Last night I was shaking my ass in the Marriott (Gucci, Gucci wants a girl they can call, they can call)
 Tonight we’re doing business, how much you got? (Gucci, Gucci wants a girl they can call, they can call)
 Ain’t nobody like me, can’t fill my spot (Gucci, Gucci wants a girl they can call, they can call)
 Count my blessings up so high man, shout out to God

Bree displays her balance of having fun and getting her coin. Bree can play but she doesn’t play with her bag.

All thanks to the Man Upstairs for her bountiful blessings and her spot that can’t be filled by anyone else.

Flexible like a split (Ah, ah) (Gucci, Gucci wants a girl they can call, they can call)
 Burnin’ up like a spliff
 Options like my wigs (Gucci, Gucci wants a girl they can call, they can call)
 They ask how I do how I did

Bree flexes her musical versatility and genre range that many artists in her caliber do not possess. She compares this by saying she has “options like [her] wigs,” which she can be seen flaunting (and bodying) in various color ranges on her social media pages and music videos.

She also declares her status of embodying the flames of cannabis by blazing the music game right now by “burnin' up like a spliff.”

Needless to say, she’s hot right now & she’s in her own lane. Period.
